europhysiology]] at Columbia-Presbyterian Hospital's [[Neurological Institute of New York]].\n\nReturning briefly to London to attend the Le Cordon Bleu London<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lcblondon.com/|title=Le Cordon Bleu London|publisher=}}</ref> (originally, the London Cordon Bleu School of Cookery), Chalmers opened her own cooking school first in Baltimore, MD, then in Greensboro, NC. She went on to become a gourmet shop owner and wine importer, pioneer author of the single subject cookbook, awarding-winning publisher, restaurant consultant, adjunct professor, columnist and mentor. Renowned for her wit and captivating insights, she continues to be a frequent commentator and keynote speaker on food and food trends. Her work has appeared in ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''[[Food & Wine]]'', ''[[Gourmet Magazine|Gourmet]]'', ''[[Gastronomica]]'', ''Food Arts'' and ''[[Nation's Restaurant News]]''.\n\nChalmers was a food essayist, ''The Last Word'' columnist for ''Chef Magazine'',<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.chefmagazine.com/digital.htm |title=''Chef Magazine'' |access-date=2015-01-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151108083901/http://www.chefmagazine.com/digital.htm |archive-date=2015-11-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref> as well as a commentator on [[WAMC]]/Northeast Public Radio,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wamc.org/|title=WAMC - Northeast Public Radio|publisher=}}</ref> while serving as a consultant, food blogger,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foodjobsbook.com/blog/|title=Blogging - Food Jobs by Irena Chalmers|date=20 February 2012|publisher=}}</ref> and mentor to many embarking on their culinary adventures. She retired from [[The Culinary Institute of America]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ciachef.edu/|title=The Culinary Institute of America : The World's Premier Culinary College|publisher=}}</ref> after teaching Professional Food Writing, Food Jobs and Gastronomy for nearly 16 years. Chalmers died on April 4, 2020.<ref>[https://www.facebook.com/irena.chalmers/posts/2503957459708464?__tn__=-R]</ref>\n\n==Author and publisher==\n\nIn 1968, when faced with how to get rid of six fondue pots languishing in her cooking school/wine and cheese shop, La Bonne Femme, Chalmers demonstrated the 'fine art' of melting cheese. This cooking demonstration led to the publication of a 48-page ''Fondue'' cookbook, ''Chocolate Surprises'' cookbook and the creation of Potpourri Press.\n\nChalmers then wrote other specialty food cookbooks, including the first microwave cookbook for Litton, the first ice cream cookbook for [[Donvier]] ice cream machines and several cookbooks commissioned by Le Creuset. The most successful of these small books was ''Napkin Folds'' for the Lillian Vernon catalog, responsible for sales of more than one million copies. Estimated total sales of the small cookbooks exceeded seven million copies worldwide.\n\nAs an editor, publisher and packager, Chalmers oversaw and contributed to many award-winning titles, successful cookbook series and food guides, including: the 'Round the World cookbooks (8 million copies sold); The Great American Cooking Schools 12-book series (designed by renowned graphic designer, [[Milton Glaser]]), winner of the Art Directors Club Award and eight R. T. French Tastemaker Awards; Books by Cooks, a 24-book series; and the Creative Cook volumes. Chalmers was the first to publish the work of many American culinary leaders, among them: ''Romantic & Classic Cakes'' by Rose Levy Beranbaum, ''American Food & California Wine'' by Barbara Kafka, ''Quiche & P\u00e2t\u00e9'' by Peter Kump and ''Christmas Feasts from History'' by Lorna Sass. She compiled ''The Food Professional's Guide'' in association with [[The James Beard Foundation]] with a foreword by [[Julia Child]].\n\nChalmers was the author of ''The Great American Food Almanac'', ''American Bistro'' and ''The Great Food Almanac''. These books were all winners of the International Association of Culinary Professionals (IACP) Julia Child Award,<ref>[http://www.iacp.com/displaycommon.cfm?an=1&subarticlenbr=100 International Association of Culinary Professionals] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081225150047/http://www.iacp.com/displaycommon.cfm?an=1&subarticlenbr=100 |date=2008-12-25 }}</ref> Her most recent book, ''Great Food Jobs 2: Ideas and Inspiration for Your Job Hunt''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foodjobsbook.com/buy-the-book/great-food-jobs|title=Great Food Jobs 2: Ideas and Inspiration for Your Job Hunt - Food Jobs by Irena Chalmers|publisher=}}</ref> received a 2013 Gourmand Special Jury Award for excellence. Her prior ''Food Jobs: 150 Great Jobs for Culinary Students, Career Changers and Food Lovers''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foodjobsbook.com/|title=Food Jobs by Irena Chalmers - Great jobs for culinary students, career changers and food lovers|publisher=}}</ref> won the 2008 Gourmand World Cookbook Award for the Best Book for Food Professionals in the U.S. and later, the 2008 Gourmand World Cookbook Award\u2014Best Book for Food Professionals in the World.<ref>[http://www.cookbookfair.com/html/paris_july_1_2009.html Cookbook Fair] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090706052914/http://www.cookbookfair.com/html/paris_july_1_2009.html |date=2009-07-06 }}</ref>\n\nChalmers was a founding member and past president of the IACP,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.iacp.com/index.cfm |title=International Association of Culinary Professionals |access-date=2009-01-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081231055030/http://www.iacp.com/index.cfm |archive-date=2008-12-31 |url-status=dead }}</ref> a culinary worldwide organization of nearly 4,000 members from more than 40 countries. She also was a founding member and past president of [[Les Dames d'Escoffier]] International (LDEI).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ldei.org/|title=Les Dames d'Escoffier International (LDEI)|publisher=}}</ref> LDEI is an invitation-only organization of women leaders in food, beverage and hospitality whose mission is education, advocacy and philanthropy.\n\nShe held a number of consulting roles at the restaurants, the [[Rainbow Room]] and [[Windows on the World]]. She worked closely for American restaurant icon [[Joe Baum]] for 14 years. She was a consultant for Epicurious.com,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.epicurious.com|title=Epicurious.com: Recipes, Menus, Cooking Articles & Food Guides|publisher=}}</ref> CuisineNet.com,<ref>[http://www.cuisinenet.com ''Cuisinenet'']</ref> FamilyTime.com,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://familytime.com|title=Welcome to Familytime.com|publisher=}}</ref> and Modern Maturity magazine, (today, AARP magazine). In addition, Chalmers was a visiting professor at New York University and the New School for Social Research and an associate of the International Food Information Council (IFIC)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ific.org|title=Welcome to IFIC Foundation|publisher=|access-date=2020-01-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080212001020/http://ific.org/|archive-date=2008-02-12|url-status=dead}}</ref> on Food Biotechnology and BIO: Council for Biotechnology Information Bureau.\n\n==Awards==\nThroughout her career Chalmers was recognized with several distinguished awards including: James Beard Foundation \"Who's Who\" Award Winner (1988 - the first year the awards were presented), Woman of the Year, New York University Center for Food and Hotel Management (1989) and 12 Tastemaker Awards for publications she  wrote or published. She received the Honor of La Bonne Vie Champenoise Award and The Doctorate of Foodservice for Exemplary Service to the Food Service Industry. She was an Ambassador of The Culinary Institute of America.\n\n==Selected publications==\n*''Great Food Jobs 2: Ideas and Inspiration for Your Job Hunt'' (2013)\n*''Food Jobs: 150 Great Jobs for Culinary Students, Career Changers and Food Lovers'' (2008)\n*''The Great Food Almanac'' (1994)\n*''Good Old Food-A Taste From The Past'' (1993)\n*''The Working Family's Cookbook'' (1993)\n*''The Food Professional's Guide'' (1990)\n*''Irena Chalmers' All-Time Favorites'' (1990)\n*''Christmas Memories with Recipes'' (1988)\n*''The Great American Christmas Almanac'' (1988)\n*''The Great American Food Almanac'' (1986)\n*''American Bistro'' (1986)\n*''Home for the Holidays'' (1980)\n*''Beginner's Book of Beautiful Food'' (1976)\n*''The Confident Cook'' (1975)<ref>{{cite web|title=Chef Magazine|url=http://www.chefmagazine.com/}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|http://www.foodjobsbook.com/ }}\n*[http://www.foodjobsbook.com/meet_irena_chalmers.html Meet Irena Chalmers]\n*[http://www.ciachef.edu/admissions/spotlight/spotlight.asp?iSpotID=241 Culinary Institute of America]\n*[http://www.cuisinenet.com/cafe/bios.htm Cuisinenet Biographies]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20151108083901/http://www.chefmagazine.com/digital.htm ''Chef Magazine'']\n*[http://www.sallys-place.com/studio/chalmers.htm Sallys-Place.com]\n*[http://www.jamesbeard.org/index.php?q=james_beard_awards_whos_who/ James Beard Awards Who's Who]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chalmers, Irena}}\n[[Category:American cookbook writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:British emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Women food writers]]\n[[Category:Women cookbook writers]]\n[[Category:Culinary Institute of America people]]\n[[Category:American women non-fiction writers]]\n", "name_user": "EditExpress", "label": "safe", "comment": "Link added.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irena_Chalmers"}
